{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772181811310,"sessionID":"ses_361bd3436ffec3i407PrX2YMFP","part":{"id":"prt_c9e446d86002fsrdHxYvLSvEqI","sessionID":"ses_361bd3436ffec3i407PrX2YMFP","messageID":"msg_c9e4467fb001mdmTbTHsz1S3IN","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_01VNCiuN4SnzZT5BQBMEiTVt","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/CONVENTIONS.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/CONVENTIONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Spec Conventions\n2: \n3: This document defines the rules, terminology, and templates that all documents\n4: under `spec/` must follow.\n5: \n6: ## Clean-Room Rules\n7: \n8: All spec documents are produced by reverse engineering — reading observable\n9: artifacts (source code, runtime logs, CLI output) rather than relying on\n10: undocumented design intent. The following rules enforce that constraint.\n11: \n12: 1. **Cite observable evidence.** Every behavioral claim must reference a source\n13:    location (file and line range) or a reproducible runtime observation.\n14: 2. **Never infer intent.** Describe what the code does, not why the author\n15:    chose to do it that way.\n16: 3. **Distinguish levels of confidence.** Use the confidence labels defined\n17:    below on any claim that is not directly confirmed by code.\n18: 4. **Do not copy source code verbatim** beyond short illustrative snippets\n19:    (five lines or fewer). Paraphrase logic in prose or pseudocode.\n20: 5. **Flag gaps explicitly.** Use the Open Questions section rather than\n21:    speculating in the body of the document.\n22: 6. **Version your observations.** Record the commit SHA or date range of the\n23:    source examined at the top of each document.\n24: \n25: ## Confidence Labels\n26: \n27: Place a label inline after any claim whose certainty is less than direct\n28: code confirmation. Labels use the format `[CONFIDENCE: <level>]`.\n29: \n30: | Label | Meaning |\n31: | --- | --- |\n32: | `[CONFIRMED]` | Directly verified in source code (cite file:line). |\n33: | `[INFERRED]` | Logically follows from confirmed facts but not directly observed. |\n34: | `[ASSUMED]` | Reasonable assumption; plausible but unverified. |\n35: | `[UNKNOWN]` | Not determinable from available evidence; add to Open Questions. |\n36: \n37: Omit the label only when the entire statement is `[CONFIRMED]` and the\n38: citation is present in the same sentence.\n39: \n40: ## Terminology\n41: \n42: | Term | Definition |\n43: | --- | --- |\n44: | **bead** | A discrete unit of work tracked by the `br` CLI. |\n45: | **epic** | A parent bead that groups related child beads. |\n46: | **iteration** | One pass of the Ralph loop: select, prompt, execute, evaluate. |\n47: | **phase** | A top-level command (`reverse`, `decompose`, `forward`). |\n48: | **run** | A single invocation of a phase command, identified by a `runId`. |\n49: | **session** | The opencode SDK conversation context for one iteration. |\n50: | **skill** | A named question set or prompt variant used during reverse. |\n51: | **template** | A Handlebars `.hbs` file that generates an agent prompt. |\n52: \n53: When introducing a term not in this table, define it in the module doc and\n54: propose adding it here via a PR comment.\n55: \n56: ## Required Section Template\n57: \n58: Every module spec must include the following sections in this order. Omit a\n59: section only if it genuinely does not apply, and note the omission with\n60: `_Not applicable for this module._`\n61: \n62: ---\n63: \n64: ```markdown\n65: # <Module Name>\n66: \n67: > One-sentence description of the module's role in the system.\n68: \n69: **Source:** `src/<filename>.ts` (examined at commit `<sha>` / `<date>`)\n70: \n71: ## Purpose\n72: \n73: Two to four sentences. What problem does this module solve and where does it\n74: sit in the overall architecture?\n75: \n76: ## Triggers\n77: \n78: What causes this module to execute? List entry points: exported functions,\n79: CLI commands, or events that invoke this module. Cite source locations.\n80: \n81: ## Inputs\n82: \n83: | Name | Type | Source | Description |\n84: |---|---|---|---|\n85: | `<name>` | `<type>` | `<caller / env / file>` | What it represents |\n86: \n87: ## Outputs\n88: \n89: | Name | Type | Destination | Description |\n90: |---|---|---|---|\n91: | `<name>` | `<type>` | `<caller / file / stdout>` | What it represents |\n92: \n93: ## Side Effects\n94: \n95: List observable effects outside the return value: file writes, environment\n96: mutations, process exits, network calls, spawned child processes.\n97: \n98: ## Failure Modes\n99: \n100: | Condition | Behavior | Recovery |\n101: |---|---|---|\n102: | `<condition>` | `<what happens>` | `<how it is handled>` |\n103: \n104: ## Dependencies\n105: \n106: | Dependency | Type | Purpose |\n107: |---|---|---|\n108: | `<name>` | internal / npm / system | Why this module uses it |\n109: \n110: ## Open Questions\n111: \n112: - List anything that could not be determined from available evidence.\n113: ```\n114: \n115: ---\n116: \n117: ## Markdown Style\n118: \n119: - Use ATX-style headings (`#`, `##`, `###`). Never use Setext underlines.\n120: - Wrap prose at 80 characters. Code blocks and tables are exempt.\n121: - Use fenced code blocks with an explicit language tag.\n122: - Prefer ordered lists for sequential steps; unordered lists for\n123:   unordered items.\n124: - Do not use bare URLs. Wrap links in Markdown link syntax.\n125: - One blank line before and after every block element (heading, list,\n126:   table, code block).\n127: - Do not use trailing spaces for line breaks. Use a blank line or HTML\n128:   `<br>` only when necessary.\n129: \n130: ## File Naming\n131: \n132: - Use lowercase kebab-case: `run-state.md`, `output-parser.md`.\n133: - Match the source filename where possible (drop the `.ts` extension).\n134: - The two meta-documents (`README.md`, `CONVENTIONS.md`) are the only\n135:   permitted uppercase filenames in `spec/`.\n\n(End of file - total 135 lines)\n</content>","title":"spec/CONVENTIONS.md","metadata":{"preview":"# Spec Conventions\n\nThis document defines the rules, terminology, and templates that all documents\nunder `spec/` must follow.\n\n## Clean-Room Rules\n\nAll spec documents are produced by reverse engineering — reading observable\nartifacts (source code, runtime logs, CLI output) rather than relying on\nundocumented design intent. The following rules enforce that constraint.\n\n1. **Cite observable evidence.** Every behavioral claim must reference a source\n   location (file and line range) or a reproducible runtime observation.\n2. **Never infer intent.** Describe what the code does, not why the author\n   chose to do it that way.\n3. **Distinguish levels of confidence.** Use the confidence labels defined\n   below on any claim that is not directly confirmed by code.\n4. **Do not copy source code verbatim** beyond short illustrative snippets\n   (five lines or fewer). Paraphrase logic in prose or pseudocode.\n5. **Flag gaps explicitly.** Use the Open Questions section rather than","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772181811301,"end":1772181811309}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772181811702,"sessionID":"ses_361bd3436ffec3i407PrX2YMFP","part":{"id":"prt_c9e447067001ZbKV69InewCtAM","sessionID":"ses_361bd3436ffec3i407PrX2YMFP","messageID":"msg_c9e4467fb001mdmTbTHsz1S3IN","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_01VXf4woinciWiSXUWzBJQ9E","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/module-catalog.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/module-catalog.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Module Catalog\n2: \n3: > Complete inventory of all source modules in the super-ralph agent framework,\n4: > grouped by domain.\n5: \n6: **Source examined at commit:** `ecc95c0` (2026-02-27)\n7: \n8: ## Coverage Key\n9: \n10: | Status | Meaning |\n11: | --- | --- |\n12: | `covered` | A detailed spec file exists in `spec/`. |\n13: | `partial` | Spec exists but is incomplete or draft. |\n14: | `todo` | No spec file yet. |\n15: \n16: ## Domains\n17: \n18: The nineteen source modules in `src/` fall into five domains:\n19: \n20: 1. [Phases](#phases) — Top-level command orchestration (3 modules)\n21: 2. [Engine](#engine) — Core iteration loop and lifecycle (1 module)\n22: 3. [Integrations](#integrations) — External service adapters (3 modules)\n23: 4. [Infrastructure](#infrastructure) — Cross-cutting support utilities (9 modules)\n24: 5. [CLI Entry Point](#cli-entry-point) — Argument parsing and dispatch (1 module)\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## Phases\n29: \n30: Phase modules implement the three top-level commands. Each module calls\n31: `runPhaseLoop` from the engine and supplies phase-specific callbacks for\n32: selecting work, building prompts, and handling results.\n33: \n34: | Module | Path | Responsibility | Status |\n35: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n36: | Forward | `src/forward.ts` | Picks the highest-priority ready bead, renders a prompt, and drives the engine until all epic beads are closed. | `todo` |\n37: | Decompose | `src/decompose.ts` | Creates an epic via `br`, then iteratively prompts the agent to read a spec file and produce beads from it. | `todo` |\n38: | Reverse | `src/reverse.ts` | Runs either an interactive SSE session (human-driven Q&A) or an autonomous loop that refines a Markdown spec document. | `todo` |\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ## Engine\n43: \n44: The engine module owns the generic iteration loop shared by all three phases.\n45: \n46: | Module | Path | Responsibility | Status |\n47: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n48: | Engine | `src/engine.ts` | Drives the select-prompt-execute-evaluate loop; manages retries, error strategy, event emission, run tracking, and timeouts. | `todo` |\n49: \n50: ---\n51: \n52: ## Integrations\n53: \n54: Integration modules wrap external services and tools behind typed interfaces\n55: used by the engine and phase modules.\n56: \n57: | Module | Path | Responsibility | Status |\n58: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n59: | opencode adapter | `src/opencode.ts` | Manages opencode server lifecycle, session creation, real-time SSE prompt streaming, and result extraction. | `todo` |\n60: | Interactive session | `src/interactive.ts` | Handles the interactive reverse mode: subscribes to SSE events, intercepts questions, and renders them via `@clack/prompts` or mock answers. | `todo` |\n61: | bead integration | `src/beads.ts` | Thin adapter around the `br` CLI: spawns child processes, parses JSON output, and returns typed `BeadInfo` objects. | `todo` |\n62: \n63: ---\n64: \n65: ## Infrastructure\n66: \n67: Infrastructure modules provide cross-cutting support — configuration, templating,\n68: persistence, event routing, and utilities — consumed by the engine and phases.\n69: \n70: | Module | Path | Responsibility | Status |\n71: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n72: | Types | `src/types.ts` | Central type definitions: all shared interfaces and type aliases used across the codebase. | `todo` |\n73: | config | `src/config.ts` | Loads and merges `.super-ralph/config.toml` with defaults; resolves AI model selection by bead labels or CLI override. | `todo` |\n74: | Template | `src/template.ts` | Loads and renders Handlebars `.hbs` prompt templates stored in `.super-ralph/`. | `todo` |\n75: | Output parser | `src/output-parser.ts` | Accumulates raw SSE event lines and display text during a session; caps total size at 250,000 characters. | `todo` |\n76: | Run state | `src/run-state.ts` | Persists per-run artifacts: timestamped run directory, live `session.json`, jsonl event log, and per-iteration transcripts. | `todo` |\n77: | Run status | `src/run-status.ts` | Read-only companion to run state; resolves a run reference and reads back session state, event counts, and transcript paths. | `todo` |\n78: | Progress | `src/progress.ts` | Appends human-readable Markdown progress entries to `progress.md` after each iteration; reads recent entries back for agent context. | `todo` |\n79: | Skills | `src/skills.ts` | Resolves a skill name or file path to its Markdown content; supports built-in skills and arbitrary user-supplied paths. | `todo` |\n80: | Timeout | `src/timeout.ts` | Races a promise against a deadline; rejects with a custom error message if the timeout elapses first. | `todo` |\n81: | Init | `src/init.ts` | Scaffolds a new project: creates `.super-ralph/`, copies templates, writes `config.toml`, installs the opencode plugin, and runs `br init`. | `todo` |\n82: | Events | `src/events.ts` | Defines the engine event union type, a lightweight pub/sub emitter, and a default console renderer for terminal output. | `todo` |\n83: \n84: ---\n85: \n86: ## CLI Entry Point\n87: \n88: | Module | Path | Responsibility | Status |\n89: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n90: | Index | `src/index.ts` | CLI entry point: parses command-line arguments and dispatches to `forward`, `decompose`, `reverse`, `init`, `status`, or `doctor`. | `todo` |\n91: \n92: ---\n93: \n94: ## Detailed Spec Files\n95: \n96: No detailed module spec files exist yet. All entries above are `todo`. As\n97: specs are written, this table will be updated to link each module entry to\n98: its `spec/<module-name>.md` file and the status column will advance to\n99: `partial` or `covered`.\n100: \n101: | Spec File | Module | Path |\n102: | --- | --- | --- |\n103: | _(none yet)_ | — | — |\n\n(End of file - total 103 lines)\n</content>","title":"spec/module-catalog.md","metadata":{"preview":"# Module Catalog\n\n> Complete inventory of all source modules in the super-ralph agent framework,\n> grouped by domain.\n\n**Source examined at commit:** `ecc95c0` (2026-02-27)\n\n## Coverage Key\n\n| Status | Meaning |\n| --- | --- |\n| `covered` | A detailed spec file exists in `spec/`. |\n| `partial` | Spec exists but is incomplete or draft. |\n| `todo` | No spec file yet. |\n\n## Domains\n\nThe nineteen source modules in `src/` fall into five domains:\n\n1. [Phases](#phases) — Top-level command orchestration (3 modules)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772181811697,"end":1772181811702}}}}
